{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.44,0.07,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with several lacerations to his arms and hands following an altercation outside a bar. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Examination of his arms and hands demonstrate normal movements at the wrist and elbow joint. When asked to extend his fingers, he is unable to fully extend his ring finger (Image). The rest of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tendons is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensor carpi radialis longus","Extensor carpi radialis brevis","Extensor digitorum communis","Extensor indicis proprius","Extensor carpi ulnaris"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor digitorum communis (EDC)\u003C/strong\u003E tendon. The EDC arises from the lateral epicondyle of the elbow and forms four tendons at the wrist, which insert into the middle and distal phalanges of each of the four fingers. Its primary action is extension of all fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joint, with some contribution to extension at the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe EDC tendon lies superficially on the dorsal aspect of the hand, making it particularly vulnerable to lacerations. In this case, the patient\u0027s inability to fully extend his ring finger while other fingers extend normally is highly suggestive of an isolated EDC tendon injury to that digit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor carpi radialis longus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor carpi radialis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily responsible for extension and radial deviation of the wrist. Injury to these tendons would result in weakness of wrist extension, which is not observed in this patient as wrist movements are reported as normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor indicis proprius\u003C/strong\u003E specifically extends the index finger. An injury to this tendon would affect the index finger\u0027s extension, which is not the case here as the problem is with the ring finger.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor carpi ulnaris\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for extension and ulnar deviation of the wrist. Like the other wrist extensors, an injury to this tendon would affect wrist movement, which is normal in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the isolated inability to extend the ring finger, with normal function of other digits and the wrist, points to a specific injury of the EDC tendon to the ring finger. This type of injury is common in hand lacerations due to the superficial location of the EDC tendons on the dorsum of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The extensor digitorum communis tendon lies superficially and is extremely susceptible to open injuries of the dorsal hand, presenting with an inability to extend the finger at the metacarpophalangeal joint.","Extensor digitorum communis injury can be diagnosed clinically by observing the patient\u0027s inability to extend a specific finger while other fingers extend normally."],"references":["Amirtharajah  M, Lattanza L. Open extensor tendon injuries. J Hand Surg Am. 2015;40:391-97. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25557773/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1236"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1236"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e000baec-c460-4127-be10-d40dc04910bf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e000baec-c460-4127-be10-d40dc04910bf.